04192nam a22005535i 9780822393412DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223934127 a10.1515/97808223934122doi  a(DE-B1597)553447  a(OCoLC)1110351818  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0470002bisacsh04a305.896/8068221090492221 aDonham, Donald L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aViolence in a Time of Liberation :bMurder and Ethnicity at a South African Gold Mine, 1994 /cDonald L. Donham. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b50 b&w photos, 2 tables, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tGroups at Cinderella in 1994 -- tLocal timeline in relation to national liberation -- tIntroduction -- t1. Picturing a South African Gold Mine -- t2. White Stories -- t3. Ways of Dying -- t4. Good Friday at Cinderella -- t5. Freeing Workers and Erasing History -- t6. Unionization from Above -- t7. Motives for Murder -- t8. The Aftermath “They Were Enjoying Our Freedom” -- tConclusion -- tPostscript Doing Fieldwork at the End of Apartheid -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow can we account for the apparent increase in ethnic violence across the globe? Donald L. Donham develops a methodology for understanding violence that shows why this question needs to be recast. He examines an incident that occurred at a South African gold mine at the moment of the 1994 elections that brought apartheid to a close. Black workers ganged up on the Zulus among them, killing two and injuring many more. While nearly everyone came to characterize the conflict as “ethnic,” Donham argues that heightened ethnic identity was more an outcome of the violence than its cause. Based on his careful reconstruction of events, he contends that the violence was not motivated by hatred of an ethnic other. It emerged, rather, in ironic ways, as capitalist managers gave up apartheid tactics and as black union activists took up strategies that departed from their stated values. National liberation, as it actually occurred, was gritty, contradictory, and incomplete. Given unusual access to the mine, Donham comes to this conclusion based on participant observation, review of extensive records, and interviews conducted over the course of a decade. Violence in a Time of Liberation is a kind of murder mystery that reveals not only who did it but also the ways that narratives of violence, taken up by various media, create ethnic violence after the fact.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEthnic conflictzSouth Africa. 0aPost-apartheid erazSouth Africa. 0aViolencezSouth Africa. 7aHISTORY / Africa / South / Republic of South Africa.2bisacsh1 aMofokeng, Santu.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393412zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822393412/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles